Photoplethysmographic (PPG) sensing, which involves a light source to emit light into tissue and a photo-detector to collect light reflected from or transmitted through the tissue, has been widely used for the measurement of many vital signs, such as SpO2, heart rate, respiration rate, and BP. The signal measured by this method represents the pulsatile blood volume changes of peripheral microvasculature induced by pressure pulse within each cardiac cycle. Traditionally, the sensing unit is in direct contact with skin. Recent research has shown that sensors can be integrated into daily living accessories or gadgets like ear-ring, glove and hat, to achieve unobtrusive measurement. Various types of PPG measuring devices at different sites of the body are summarized in Table II.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
